The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, August 27, 2004 				 LIC plans for seniors on cards
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Aug. 26: Life Insurance Corporation of India (LIC) plans to design schemes for senior citizens. To help sell these policies, the state-run behemoth, which is eyeing a 35 per cent business growth for 2004-05, has entered into its first corporate agency relationship with a non-governmental organisation (NGO)  HelpAge India  which works with the aged. 																								Later this year, LIC will launch around four policies. These will include a unit-linked pension plan, an endowment-based pension plan, a children money-back policy and one aimed at the high-income group with a minimum sum assured of Rs 10 lakh.																								LIC chairman S. B. Mathur said the life insurer expects to collect Rs 11,800 crore as new individual premia and another Rs 4,000 crore as new group premium in the current fiscal. However, as the base expands, the growth may come down a little, he said. In all, its overall business is likely to touch Rs 15,800 crore.  LIC Housing plans																								LIC Housing Finance plans to raise $50 million through global depository receipts over the next two months.																								Mathur said, International broking house CLSA and Kotak Securities have been appointed lead managers to the issue. 
